<HEADLINE>
Flash flood kills at least 17 in northwest Pakistan
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A flash flood killed at least 17 people in a remote northwestern
Pakistani village Friday with scores more feared dead after it
swept away at least 40 people, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The flood caused by torrential rain hit the Oshai Darray village
in Upper Dir district of North West Frontier Province around 4:30
pm (1130 GMT).
</P>
<P>
"Seventeen bodies have been recovered after about 40 to 50 people
were swept away by flooding," local mayor Sardar Tariqullah told
AFP by telephone from Upper Dir, some 320 kilometres (200 miles)
northwest of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"The calamity has devastated the area and rescue efforts are
under way, but we need help on an urgent basis," Tariqullah said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the death toll was "likely to rise."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has suffered a wave of extreme weather in the past
month.
</P>
<P>
Floods unleashed by a tropical cyclone and torrential monsoon
rains in the south and southwest of the country have claimed more
than 200 lives and affected some 1.6 million people.
</P>
<P>
Around 40 people have also been killed in recent months in
accidents caused by monsoon rains along Pakistan's rugged
northwestern border with Afghanistan.
</P>
